Kaggle Competition: Predicting House Prices

Florence Muriuki

12 July 2017

Objective

To predict house prices based on a data set from Kaggle House Prices Competition

Process

  1. Read the data into R and understand its structure and variables

  2. Preprocess the data

  3. Select features to use in the predictive model

  4. Create various predictive model and select the best based on RMSE

  5. Submit predictions to Kaggle

Structure of the data

The training data has 1460 rows and 81 columns inclusive of the response variable - SalePrice. The testing data has 1459 rows and 80 columns exclusive of the response variable - SalePrice. The first column on both data sets is an Id column indicating the sequential number of row and the rest are variables describing the houses. We combine the training data (having removed SalePrice and Id) and testing data(having removed Id) to ensure similar preprocessing of both data sets. The combined data has 2919 rows and 79 variables.

Dealing with missing values

PoolQC - Pool Quality

nrow(df[df$PoolArea > 0,]) It turns out only 13 houses have a swimming pool meaning 2906 do not have a pool.We have 3 observations with a pool but NA in PoolQC column. The 2903 without a pool should take value None to indicate they do not have a pool.

df[df$PoolArea > 0 & is.na(df$PoolQC), c("PoolArea", "PoolQC")]
##      PoolArea PoolQC
## 2421      368   <NA>
## 2504      444   <NA>
## 2600      561   <NA>
tapply(df$PoolArea, df$PoolQC, mean)
##     Ex     Fa     Gd 
## 359.75 583.50 648.50
df$PoolQC = as.character(df$PoolQC)
df[c(2421, 2504), "PoolQC"] = "Ex"
df[2600, "PoolQC"] = "Fa"
df$PoolQC[is.na(df$PoolQC)] = "None" 
df$PoolQC = as.factor(df$PoolQC)

MiscFeature - Miscellaneous features such as sheds, elevators, 2nd garage etc

In the MiscVal column (Value of miscellaneous features) we see that 2816 observations take value zero while in the MiscFeature there are 2814 observations. sizeVarsSkew = sapply(df[,sizeVars], skewness)
print(sizeVarsSkew)# all of them are skewed. We can't use log because log(0) = inf. Use min-max technique
##   TotalBsmtSF     GrLivArea     X1stFlrSF     X2ndFlrSF  LowQualFinSF 
##     1.1568941     1.2693577     1.4696044     0.8616747    12.0887610 
##    WoodDeckSF   OpenPorchSF EnclosedPorch   ScreenPorch    X3SsnPorch 
##     1.8424328     2.5351137     4.0038912     3.9466937    11.3760647 
##      PoolArea    GarageArea       LotArea 
##    16.8983279     0.2392569    12.8224314
minmax = function(x){
return ((x - min(x))/(max(x) - min(x)))
  }
df[, sizeVars] = sapply(df[,sizeVars], minmax)
df[,c("BsmtFinSF1", "BsmtFinSF2", "BsmtUnfSF")] = sapply(df[,c("BsmtFinSF1", "BsmtFinSF2","BsmtUnfSF")], minmax)
pairs.panels(cbind(df[1:1460,sizeVars], log(SalePrice)))

Predicting house prices using random forest and variables selected using boruta package

set.seed(1)
numFolds = trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)
mtryGrid = expand.grid(.mtry = c(7, 14, 21, 28, 35, 49, 51))
train(LogSalePrice ~., data = trainBoruta, method = "rf", trControl = numFolds, tuneGrid = mtryGrid, metric = "RMSE") #RMSE at mtry = 51 is 0.1364
